Koichi Fujita (藤田浩一 Fujita Kōichi; born March 20, 1947 in Chiba, Chiba Prefecture, Japan – October 11, 2009 in Kawasaki City, Kanagawa Prefecture) was a Japanese guitarist, lyricist, composer, record producer, and businessman.
Fujita was born on March 20, 1947 in Chiba, Chiba Prefecture, Japan.
As a child, he loved playing football, but spent most of his days alone because his mother died and his father remarried.
He was scouted by Watanabe Productions and debuted in 1967 as a member of Out Cast.
He left in the summer of 1967 after writing three songs, and would form The Love with Yuji Takamiya, Arai Hideo, Yasufumi Tajima (known as "Fumio Shimada" and "Heckel Tajima"), and Hiroshi Kobata.

In 1983, Kiyotaka Sugiyama & Omega Tribe debuted with "Summer Suspicion", which peaked at No. 9 on the Oricon charts.
